Creating an automatic table of contents in a LaTeX document is a fundamental aspect of organizing and navigating through the various sections and subsections of your document. LaTeX provides a straightforward way to achieve this through its built-in functionalities. Below is a step-by-step example showcasing how to generate a table of contents, including the necessary commands:

### Step 1: Preambles and Document Class

First, you start with the preambles where you include necessary packages and define document-wide settings. Then, you begin the document with the appropriate document class. For a typical article or report, you might use the `article` or `report` class.

```latex
\documentclass{article} % or use 'report' for a more extensive document

\usepackage{hyperref} % Optional, for clickable links in the TOC and cross-references

\begin{document}
```

### Step 2: Using Sections and Subsections

To make a table of contents meaningful, you need to structure your document using sectioning commands (`\section`, `\subsection`, `\subsubsection`, etc.). These commands help LaTeX understand the document structure and generate the table of contents accordingly.

```latex
\title{Example Document}
\author{Author Name}
\date{Date}

\maketitle

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction section.

\subsection{Background}
This subsection provides background information.

\section{Main Body}
\subsection{First Main Section}
Content of the first main section goes here.

\subsubsection{Sub-subsection}
Further details under the first main section.

\section{Conclusion}
This section concludes the document.
```

### Step 3: Generating the Table of Contents

To automatically generate the table of contents, you use the `\tableofcontents` command after the `\begin{document}` line but before any sectioning commands (though it's generally good practice to place it right after the document title and author information). LaTeX will compile the information from your sectioning commands and create a table of contents that reflects the structure of your document.

```latex
\tableofcontents % This command generates the table of contents
